Pholcidae , or daddy long-legs spiders, are among the most species rich spider families (
), but most of this diversity is within only two subfamilies that have speciated extensively in humid tropical forests. In the New World, this is mainly Modisiminae (currently 530 described species), while in the Old World it is Pholcinae (1077 species). Representatives of these two subfamilies can be found in a wide range of forest microhabitats, which probably explains their rich diversity also in terms of body size, shape, coloration, leg length, and ecology (
). Even congeneric species in Modisiminae and Pholcinae are sometimes superficially extremely different from each other (e.g., in
Mesabolivar González-Sponga
and
Belisana Thorell
;
, 2018).

The other three currently known subfamilies, Arteminae, Ninetinae , and Smeringopinae , are largely restricted to dryer habitats and appear to be much less diverse, both in terms of species numbers (together currently 330 species) and with respect to morphology and ecology. The limited number of different microhabitats in dry environments means that congeneric species necessarily tend to occupy similar microhabitats. As a result, they are often indistinguishable in the field and can only be separated by details of genital morphology or molecular data (e.g.,
; Huber 2022;
).

With currently 54 described species, Ninetinae is the smallest subfamily in Pholcidae . The subfamily was originally established for a species from the Arabian Peninsula (
), and further species have been described from Africa (e.g.,
), but the large majority of currently known Ninetinae live in the New World. Here they are largely restricted and adapted to ‘unfavourable’ habitats with extreme temperatures, low humidity, and limited biodiversity. It is thus unsurprising that they hold several records for the family: the southernmost locality ( 47.687°S ; an unidentified species of
Gertschiola Brignoli
; M.A. Izquierdo pers. comm., 31 Jan. 2022 ), the northernmost locality ( 56.097°N ;
Pholcophora americana Banks
;
), and the highest locality ( 4450 m a.s.l.;
Nerudia centaura Huber
;
). Most Ninetinae live in tiny spaces at ground level, under stones, in dead wood and cacti, or in the leaf litter. As a result, the spiders are small (body length usually 1–2 mm ) and short-legged, very unlike the ‘typical’ Pholcidae .

Another major gap of knowledge in Ninetinae concerns distribution. This is well exemplified by the genus that is the focus of the present contribution.
Galapa Huber
was originally established for two species from Galapagos (
), and for two decades the genus was considered endemic to the archipelago. In 2020, a newly discovered Venezuelan spider was assigned to
Galapa
, suggesting a much wider distribution, but the assignment was based on specific similarities rather than on a formal analysis (
). Here, we provide the first such analysis, supporting the systematic placement of the Venezuelan species. In addition, we describe two new species and provide new records for
Galapa
from Colombia and Costa Rica , allowing us to model the potential distribution of the genus. Finally, we provide the first extensive SEM data of four species, complementing recent comparable data on related genera (
, b, c) as a basis for an upcoming cladistic morphological analysis of Ninetinae .

