Multiple sequence alignment (MSA) and tree construction. The CO1 barcodes were translated into protein sequences using BioPython (version 1.78) (

) with invertebrate mitochondrial genetic code. Next, protein-MSAs were constructed using the mafft-linsi algorithm of MAFFT (version 7.487) (

), which then assisted the construction of nucleotide level MSAs with PAL2NAL (

). This helps avoid the introduction of biologically meaningless frameshifts to the alignments (

). A neighbor-joining (NJ) tree (

) and genetic distances among specimens were calculated using the Kimura 2-parameter model (

) in MEGA 11 (

), during which pairwise deletion of gaps in the alignment was applied. The NJ tree was assessed with 500 bootstrap replications (

). The online tool iTOL (

) was used for tree visualization.

We ran a species distribution modelling (SDM) using all 

Galapa
species

records combined. This approach disregards individual species environmental thresholds, but it serves as a qualitative exploratory analysis to assess the sampling bias for the genus by modelling areas with high suitability (for examples of similar studies with other spiders, see 

; 

). The SDM was carried out using the 19 climatic variables available in WorldClim 2.1 (

), mean tree density (

), mean canopy height (

), and global aridity index (

), all at 
1 km
2
scale. All layers were clipped using ArcMap 10.8 (Environmental Systems Research Institute, Redlands, CA) at about 500 and 
700 km
from the most northern and southern records of 

Galapa

, respectively. The spatial autocorrelation between the predictor layers was removed by performing a principal component analysis (PCA) using the corresponding function in the BioDinamica package in Dinamica EGO (

). In the SDM, we used all axes that explained at least the variation expected by chance (i.e., for 22 axes, each axis that explained at least 4.54% of the proportional variance). The modelling was performed using a raw output, with a maximum of 1000 interactions, a random test percentage of 25%, removing duplicates from the same gridcell, random seed, and 15 bootstrap replicates. This is the same set of parameters as in 

, following the recommendations by 

. The map representing the median of the replicates was adjusted with a 2.5 standard deviations stretched symbology in ArcMap 10.8. The results are discussed based on the known distribution of pholcids from northern South America and Central America, gathered from a database combining all published and unpublished records known to us (B.A. Huber & L.S. Carvalho, unpubl. data). Neotropical regionalization followed 

and 

