Natural history . Representatives of the genus
Galapa
appear restricted to semi-arid and sun-exposed habitats where they occupy the leaf litter, spaces under stones, and dead cacti and dry branches lying on the ground and hollowed by termites (
). We never found them in neighboring, more forested, shaded, and humid sites. When disturbed, they ran rapidly. In glass vials, both males and females built small webs on which they were seen resting a few hours after being captured (
). Egg-sacs are flat (a single layer of eggs) and contain up to six eggs that are wrapped by a few barely visible silk lines; egg diameters range from 0.38 to 0.43 mm . For further information, see individual natural history sections below.

